07861nam a22012135i 9783110254389DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20112011gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)763160678  a97831102543897 a10.1515/97831102543892doi  a(DE-B1597)123527  a(OCoLC)748093663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP99 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481ua302.2092qDE-101222/ger00aSemiotics Continues to Astonish :bThomas A. Sebeok and the Doctrine of Signs /ced. by Paul Cobley, John Deely, Kalevi Kull, Susan Petrilli. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (526 p.) :bfrontispiece  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSemiotics, Communication and Cognition [SCC] ,x1867-0873 ;v70 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeirce's (1906) proposal that the universe as a whole, even if it does not consist exclusively of signs, is yet everywhere perfused with signs, is a thesis that better than any other sums up the life and work of Thomas A. Sebeok, "inventor" of semiotics as we know it today. Semiotics - the doctrine of signs - has a long and intriguing history that extends back well beyond the last century, two and a half millennia to Hippocrates of Cos. It ranges through the teachings of Augustine, Scholastic philosophy, the work of Peirce and Saussure. Yet a fully-fledged doctrine of signs, with many horizons for the future, was the result of Sebeok's work in the twentieth century. The massive influence of this work, as well as Sebeok's convening of semiotic projects and encouragement of a huge number of researchers globally, which, in turn, set in train countless research projects, is difficult to document and has not been assessed until now. This volume, using the testimonies of key witnesses and participants in the semiotic project, offers a picture of how Sebeok, through his development of knowledge of endosemiotics, phytosemiotics, biosemiotics and sociosemiotics, enabled semiotics in general to redraw the boundaries of science and the humanities as well as nature and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aSemiotics. 4aKommunikation. 4aSemiotik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCommunication.  aSemiotics.1 aAnderson, Myrdene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehar, Lisa Block de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrier, Søren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobley, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobley, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCunningham, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanesi, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeely, Brooke Williams, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeely, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeely, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGorlée, Dinda L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmeyer, Jesper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohansen, Jørgen Dines, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKull, Kalevi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKull, Kalevi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMladenov, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeţ, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPern, Tanel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go